 Southeast Asia, does the shifting geopolitics of energy give these big powers a new strategic tool in an intensifying rivalry with China? Or does the changing geopolitics of energy resources create more areas of shared interests and opportunities for cooperation between these big powers to balance, rather than increase, tensions in Southeast Asia? This book will be of interest to anyone who is keen to learn how the world, especially the United States, can accommodate and adapt to the new global energy dynamics and how China and ASEAN operate as new players in global and regional energy markets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChina--Foreign economic relations--Southeast Asia. 0aChina--Foreign relations--Southeast Asia. 0aEnergy consumptionzChina. 0aEnergy consumptionzSoutheast Asia. 0aEnergy consumption--China. 0aEnergy consumption--Southeast Asia. 0aEnergy policy--China. 0aEnergy policy--Southeast Asia. 0aEnergy securityzChina. 0aEnergy securityzSoutheast Asia. 0aSoutheast AsiaxForeign relationszChina. 0aSoutheast Asia--Foreign economic relations--China. 0aSoutheast Asia--Foreign relations--China. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Energy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPP Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070099240uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469526840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695268423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97898146952